[start section id="20112"]

#1 Stage II colon cancer
Mr. Brown is a 76-year-old gentleman who was recently found to have a colon mass after he presented with fatigue and anemia.  He underwent surgery, and pathology revealed stage II colon cancer.  We discussed with Mr. Brown and his wife that there is very high likelihood that he is cured with surgery.  We discussed that treatment with chemotherapy is controversial with his stage of disease.  We did discuss that the fact that he does not have microsatellite instability puts him at indeterminate risk.  If he decides to pursue chemotherapy, then the standard chemotherapy option would be FOLFOX regimen.  The patient is interested in pursuing oral capecitabine.  We did discuss that this medication might not be approved for stage II treatment.  We discussed possibility of enrolling in a clinical trial that is actually open in his hometown.  That is the E5202 trial performing 18q genetic analysis and then randomizing patients to either no treatment if they are deemed low-risk or to treatment with FOLFOX plus or minus Avastin.  We discussed that this might be a good option for the patient as it may mean that he really does not need any further chemotherapy.  Mr. Brown would like to think about this.  He wants to think whether he would like to pursue treatment closer to home or at SMCCHC.  He is also strongly considering starting oral capecitabine.  He will contact his insurance and find out whether this medication would be covered for him.  All questions were answered.  I also filled return-to-work form for the patient and provided him with a return-to-work letter. He works as a valet part-time at a local hospital.
#2 Nausea
The patient describes persistent nausea and diarrhea since his contrast study. Somewhat unusual to have delayed symptoms at this point from allergic reaction. One could consider viral gastroenteritis. I provided the patient with prescription for compazine to use as-needed for nausea.
ADVANCE DIRECTIVES
Advance directive or living will: Yes, not on file at SMCCHC.
PATIENT EDUCATION
Ready to learn, no apparent learning barriers were identified; learning preferences include listening.  Explained diagnosis and treatment plan; patient expressed understanding of the content.

