[start section id="20103"]

Mr. Brown is a pleasant 76-year-old gentleman from Pennsylvania.
Mr. Brown's history is as follows:
1)  In 2005 he had a colonoscopy performed with removal of several small polyps.  Recommended repeat scope in two-to-three years.
2)  July 23, 2010, presented to his provider with fatigue and was found to be anemic with a hemoglobin of 6.6.  He underwent blood transfusions as well as iron administration.
3)  July 27, 2010, presented to SMCCHC for further workup.  A colonoscopy performed to the cecum noting a 3-mm polyp in the ascending colon that was removed.  Also in the ascending colon near the hepatic flexure was a cauliflower like polypoid mass that was 3 to 4-cm, friable, and encased one-third of the circumference.  Also noted was an intact 3 to 4-mm polyp in the transverse colon.  Pathology of the polyp was a tubular adenoma with low-grade dysplasia.  A biopsy of the ascending mass positive for invasive moderately differentiated adenocarcinoma.
4)  July 30, 2010, CT abdomen and pelvis noting a barely identifiable thickening of the ascending colon.  Tiny low-density focus in the right lobe of the liver times two which is too small to characterize, probable cyst.  Stable subpleural nodules in the right lower lung.  An aortic abdominal aneurysm graft repair with an endo leak that is stable.
5)  August 16, 2010, Dr. Bradley performed a right hemicolectomy.  Pathology is positive for moderately differentiated grade 3 (of 4) adenocarcinoma in the ascending colon.  Surgical resected margins are negative.  All of 21 regional lymph nodes negative for metastatic disease (T3, N0).  Results of microsatellite instability did not demonstrate the presence of defective DNA mismatch repair function within the tumor (MSS/MSI-L).
Mr. Brown is here today with his wife to talk about results of the testing and any additional treatment options for his stage II colorectal carcinoma.  He reports recovering quite well from the surgery, and he was really feeling great until yesterday when he had developed nausea after drinking oral contrast dye in Radiology.  Since then, he has had persistent diarrhea and nausea.  He denies ever having any reaction to contrast agent before.
He denies any fevers, chills, abdominal pain, vision problems, or headache.  He does not have any persistent bony aches or pains.  He was not losing weight prior to the diagnosis or currently.

